      The board
   =20
 =20
It is an exaggeration, but a useful one, to say that Twitter=E2=80=99s boar=
d of directors is made up of 11 people who don=E2=80=99t use Twitter and do=
n=E2=80=99t own any Twitter stock. Actually one member of the board =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0though he is scheduled to step down next month =E2=80=94=C2=A0is J=
ack Dorsey, a founder of Twitter, who (1) owns 2.4% of the company, (2) use=
s the product and (3) does not seem to get along with the other directors. =
The other 10 directors all own=C2=A0a little stock =E2=80=94=C2=A0about 0.2=
% of the company, total, among them =E2=80=94=C2=A0and I=E2=80=99m sure the=
y all have Twitter accounts and tweet occasionally.[3] But if your model of=
 Twitter=E2=80=99s board was =E2=80=9Cthis is a collection of=C2=A0fancy im=
portant smart successful business and tech people who have no particular co=
nnection to Twitter,=E2=80=9D that would, I think, be mostly fine? Some pub=
lic tech companies have boards made up of, like, the founder and a handful =
of venture capitalists who backed the company from the beginning and are pa=
ssionate believers in the company=E2=80=99s product and mission. Twitter=E2=
=80=99s board isn=E2=80=99t like that.Twitter is a strange company; it has =
enormous influence on politics and culture but is not great at making money=
. It has a lot of power as a venue of public discussion, and there is a lot=
 of debate among Twitter=E2=80=99s employees and users, and among politicia=
ns and regulators, about how it should use that power. Elon Musk certainly =
cares about this stuff, and has explicitly said that he wants to buy Twitte=
r not for economic reasons but for =E2=80=9Cfree speech.=E2=80=9DYou could =
imagine a board of directors of a publicly traded company with an important=
 social purpose=C2=A0caring about that purpose=C2=A0as it decides whether o=
r not to sell the company. You could imagine Twitter=E2=80=99s board thinki=
ng things like =E2=80=9CTwitter will be better for the world if Elon Musk o=
wns it than if it is owned by the public,=E2=80=9D[4] or =E2=80=9CTwitter w=
ill be worse for the world if Elon Musk owns it.=E2=80=9D You could imagine=
 the board declining to sell to Musk if it thinks his ownership would be ba=
d. Or you could imagine it negotiating some sort of protections for the pro=
duct =E2=80=94=C2=A0some commitment by Musk not to do some bad things, not =
to censor his critics or whatever, or=C2=A0some independent review board to=
 protect the product under Musk=E2=80=99s ownership =E2=80=94=C2=A0before a=
greeing to sell. (Of course it is hard to imagine Musk=C2=A0agreeing=C2=A0t=
o that; he wants Twitter because it is  his favorite toy and he wants it to=
 work exactly the way he wants.)Now, to be clear, if the board did any of t=
his, the goal would not be to preserve value for the shareholders. If Elon =
Musk buys Twitter for $54.20 per share, Twitter=E2=80=99s public shareholde=
rs will get $54.20 and won=E2=80=99t own Twitter anymore. If Musk=E2=80=99s=
 actions crash the value of the company, or increase it, that has nothing t=
o do with the public shareholders; they=E2=80=99ll be gone. As a fiduciary =
for the shareholders, if the board is selling the company for cash it has n=
o real reason to demand any constraints on how Musk runs the company.=C2=A0=
But we live in a world of =E2=80=9Cstakeholder capitalism,=E2=80=9D where a=
 company=E2=80=99s board of directors is expected to consider not only shar=
eholder value but also what is best for the company=E2=80=99s community and=
 users and employees and other stakeholders. You could imagine Twitter=E2=
=80=99s board saying =E2=80=9C$54.20 is a fair price for Twitter=E2=80=99s =
shareholders, but it is bad for the community and users and employees so we=
 will say no.=E2=80=9D You could imagine it going the other way! The direct=
ors might think that Musk=E2=80=99s ownership would be good for the communi=
ty and users and employees; Dorsey seems to think that.But mostly my impres=
sion is that they are not particularly thinking about it? Twitter=E2=80=99s=
 importance for the world is obvious to many of its users, and to politicia=
ns, and certainly to Elon Musk. I am not sure that the board has noticed it=
!Incidentally, the legal standard here is a bit odd. Roughly speaking, the =
way Delaware law works is that a board can=C2=A0reject a cash acquisition f=
or stakeholder-y reasons, but it can=E2=80=99t really=C2=A0accept=C2=A0one =
for those reasons. =E2=80=9CWe will not sell to Elon Musk because it would =
be bad for the world for him to own Twitter, even though the price is right=
,=E2=80=9D is a controversial but possible thing for the board to say. =E2=
=80=9CWe will sell to Elon Musk because it would be good for the world for =
him to own Twitter, even though the price is wrong,=E2=80=9D would not be o=
kay.[5] Similarly, if the board did sell to Musk but demanded protections f=
or the product, for the good of its users and society, shareholders might r=
easonably complain that it did not maximize price. But this is all hypothet=
ical, because Twitter=E2=80=99s board seems to have an old-school focus on =
maximizing shareholder value.=C2=A0
