f fundamental corporate valuation, got a value for Twitter of about $46 per=
 share=C2=A0last week, and was open to the possibility of a higher number. =
I am being too harsh in suggesting that the bankers had to strain their mod=
els to get to $54.20. But I also doubt that they just fired up a basic mode=
l with conservative assumptions and got an $80 price right away. (Also neit=
her Damodaran nor I are looking at Twitter=E2=80=99s own management case; h=
e=E2=80=99s using somewhat generous growth assumptions.) From a fundamental=
 valuation perspective, $54.20 is not a preemptive offer but it is, you kno=
w, fine.[2] In a past life I was a mergers-and-acquisitions lawyer. Which m=
eant working all weekend a lot, and occasionally meant sitting in a confere=
nce room with a public company=E2=80=99s board as the sun came up on Monday=
 morning, frantically drafting a merger press release to go out at like 9 a=
.m.=C2=A0[3] Also one of them, Egon Durban, represents Silver Lake Group, w=
hich owns 2.1 million Twitter shares=C2=A0and also $1 billion of its=C2=A0c=
onvertible bonds.[4] This is a somewhat weird thing to think: You are the b=
oard, you should just make it better for the world! But I think it is plaus=
ible to imagine that there are public-company constraints on action that go=
 away if the company is private. (You might imagine that Twitter's board wo=
uld like to make the product better for the world, but feels constrained by=
 the need to maximize shareholder value.) Also just if Elon Musk shows you =
his plan for the company and you are like =E2=80=9Cthis is a really good pl=
an, much better than we could have come up with=E2=80=9D then arguably you =
should let him have it.[5] I am oversimplifying. Here is a Wachtell, Lipton=
, Rosen & Katz memo advocating for stakeholder governance generally, and me=
ntioning =E2=80=9CRevlon duties=E2=80=9D in a sale of the company for cash =
as a special exception.=C2=A0[6] I am assuming a stock price of about $1,00=
0 per share for Tesla, and $54.20 per share (Musk=E2=80=99s deal price) for=
 Twitter.[7] If you just look at Twitter's top 10 holders you get to 45% of=
 the stock held by holders who own more Tesla (by dollar value), though tha=
t counts Musk, which maybe you shouldn=E2=80=99t.=C2=A0
