</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Sure this=C2=A0<em>feels=C2=A0</em>wei=
rd, but it=E2=80=99s actually pretty normal, except for all the tweeting. A=
 bidder offers to buy a public company for cash at a premium to its market =
price, say for $54.20 per share. The reaction of the company=E2=80=99s boar=
d is, as it usually is: No, we=E2=80=99re worth much more than that. It qui=
ckly puts in place <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click=
/27485978.273602/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLz=
IwMjItMDQtMTgvdHdpdHRlci1oYXMtYS1wb2lzb24tcGlsbC1ub3c_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDQyNTIyX=
01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rl=
cm09MjIwNDI1JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB595b3=
2d0" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-c=
olor: #ccc;"> defensive measures</a> so it can take its time to consider th=
e bid and its next steps.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The next steps ar=
e pretty standard. One thing the board does is ask the bidder to pay a bit =
more: =E2=80=9CLook, these defensive measures can stop you, but if you can =
pay $69 per share we=E2=80=99ve got a deal.=E2=80=9D Another thing is to lo=
ok for another buyer who might pay a higher price: The company is in play, =
so if there=E2=80=99s anyone else who might buy it now is the time. Sometim=
es, though, there is only one natural buyer for a company, so there will no=
t be much competition. Other times, I guess, there will be=C2=A0<em>zero=C2=
=A0</em>natural buyers for a company and one unnatural vanity buyer, and th=
en there definitely won=E2=80=99t be much competition.</p><p style=3D"margi=
n: 16px 0;">Another thing the board will do =E2=80=94=C2=A0something it mig=
ht not do very often, outside of a takeover bid=E2=80=94=C2=A0is=C2=A0<em>t=
ry to figure out how much the company is worth</em>. The company=E2=80=99s =
management will sharpen its financial projections, the board will hire inve=
stment bankers, the bankers will take the projections and feed them into a =
financial model, the model will spit out some value for the company, the va=
lue will be upsettingly low, the senior investment banker will look at the =
value and say =E2=80=9Cno no no we can=E2=80=99t show the board that, what =
terminal growth rate are you using,=E2=80=9D the junior bankers will tweak =
the model until it makes a horrible clattering noise and bolts start poppin=
g off, the revised model will produce a range of values that includes the b=
idder=E2=80=99s price of $54.20, the senior banker will present the results=
 to the board and whisper =E2=80=9Chey this is actually pretty generous,=E2=
=80=9D and the board will swallow and say =E2=80=9Chuh okay $54.20 isn=E2=
=80=99t so bad then.=E2=80=9D[1]</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Meanwhile,=
 the board will be calling=C2=A0shareholders, the bidder will be calling sh=
areholders, and the shareholders will be calling the board. Generally speak=
ing, the board will be telling shareholders =E2=80=9Cour standalone plan is=
 worth more than $54.20 in cash,=E2=80=9D the bidder will be telling shareh=
olders =E2=80=9C$54.20 in cash is worth more than their standalone plan,=E2=
=80=9D and the shareholders will be telling the board what they think. If t=
he shareholders all tell the board =E2=80=9Cwe think $54.20 in cash is wort=
h more than your standalone plan, you should sell,=E2=80=9D it will be hard=
 for the board to reject the bid. It will still try to negotiate a higher p=
rice, of course, and to find other bidders. But if the shareholders all wan=
t to sell at $54.20, the board will have a hard time rejecting the deal ent=
irely. It=C2=A0<em>can:=C2=A0</em>The board has a fiduciary duty to use its=
 independent judgment about whether or not to sell the company; even if the=
 shareholders disagree the board can say no. But the more vocally the share=
holders want a deal, the harder it is in practice for the board to say no.<=
/p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">(On the other hand, if the shareholders all=
 say =E2=80=9Cwe love the company just the way it is, don=E2=80=99t sell,=
=E2=80=9D the board will cheerfully reject the offer.)</p><p style=3D"margi=
n: 16px 0;">If the board concludes that its standalone valuation is not so =
hot =E2=80=94=C2=A0that $54.20 wasn=E2=80=99t the insulting offer the board=
 first assumed =E2=80=94=C2=A0and if the shareholders suggest to the board =
that they=E2=80=99d like to take the money, then the board will start negot=
iating with the bidder. They will negotiate on price, if possible, but the =
board may not have much leverage to push there. And they will negotiate on =
the boring second-order mergers-and-acquisitions things, which basically co=
me down to deal certainty. If the board is going to sell for $54.20, it wil=
l want to be very sure of getting the $54.20. It will want reassurances tha=
t the bidder has financing lined up, and that the bidder can=E2=80=99t walk=
 away if anything goes wrong with the financing. It will want assurances on=
 regulatory and antitrust matters and everything else that might blow up a =
deal. It will want the bidder to agree to pay a big breakup fee if for some=
 reason the deal does fall apart.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">(On the o=
ther hand, the board will want to maximize=C2=A0<em>its=C2=A0</em>flexibili=
ty, and its shareholders=E2=80=99 ability=C2=A0to get out of the deal. It w=
ill negotiate for the ability to terminate the deal if a better offer comes=
 along, for instance. The deal will be subject to a shareholder vote, and i=
f the bidder already owns a big block of shares the board will want to=C2=
=A0negotiate a requirement that the deal be approved by a majority of the=
=C2=A0<em>other=C2=A0</em>shareholders, i.e., that the bidder=E2=80=99s own=
 votes won=E2=80=99t count.)</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The traditiona=
l time to negotiate all of this is from like 4:01 p.m. on Friday through 9:=
29 a.m. on Monday, because that gives you like 65 consecutive hours when th=
e U.S. stock market is not open and you can have material conversations wit=
hout disclosing them. So nobody sleeps from Friday evening through Monday m=
orning, and you hopefully button up the deal by then.[2] If not, you take a=
 nap and work through the night on Monday.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=
I don=E2=80=99t know anything but it does look like Elon Musk is=C2=A0going=
 to buy Twitter! The <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/cli=
ck/27485978.273602/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud3NqLmNvbS9hcnRpY2xlcy90d2l0dGVyLXJlLWV4=
